<br>
<br>
34 Peridots today, in 4 hours... and I have RS3. 47 Frog record, though.... cleared all of Disco on 1 pull.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
The *best* AE groups I've done have been 2 wizards, 1 magician, 2 enchanters, 1 cleric. Preferably both wizards have epic, and do the pulling. I also like to pull, but burn a hell of a lot of peridots doing it. Magician summons God Rods and focus items. Enchanters stun.<br>
<br>
Also very good if the Magician can CoH. People *will* die in an AE group. Bind outside, zone back in when you die, get CoH'd, and rez/loot corpse after the pull.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
The problem that most people seem to have with AE groups is that they think it isn't fair that we can kill 50+ frogs on a pull.  What people don't realize is just how dangerous it is to do this: I have 500 unbuffed AC, compared to the over a thousand a 57 SK or Monk can have. If I get stunned, it's almost sure death, even with an 800 point rune and 2500 buffed hitpoints, because I'm pulling trains. Even with all that, and assuming I make it back to the camp, mobs still have a round to pound on me before they get hit with the stun cycle, and they can do a lot of damage in that round. Especially if I'm pulling big trains, instead of 4-5 per pull. In 4 hours today, I died twice, and wasn't the only one to die. In most groups, that would be considered terrible.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, if the enchanter gets stunned, it's almost definitely a wipeout. Even the best AE groups still wipe from time to time: just ask Rakot.<br>
<br>
<br>
Lastly, melees hate AE groups because of what we're capable of, but don't realize that if it hadn't been for zones like Dreadlands and Velk's, wizards would actually be wanted in &quot;normal&quot; groups. If that had happened, AE groups probably wouldn't be anywhere near as commonplace as they are. As it stands, melees don't like us, and I'll take 1.5 blue/train, 50+ frog pulls, thank you.<br>
<br>
